@2777  = ~This ring has an inscription on the inside that looks like the *real* claim to this inn. Why would you be the owner when this claim says different?~
@2778  = ~Follow me closely inside as well. I fancy there no be a more dangerous a building in all o' Baldur's Gate. Can you think o' anywhere better equipped against thieves than the Thieves' Guild itself? Could teach Durlag's Tower a thing or three, I daresay.~
@2779  = ~~
@2780  = ~Oh, so now you've stooped to forcing your way into locked containers in people's houses, have you? Before you accuse ME of doing anything wrong, maybe you should look to YOURSELF. You're a PALADIN, right? What's a holier-than-thou soldier doing forcing locks, eh?~
@2781  = ~Oh, so you knew it was locked upstairs?~
@2782  = ~I can't condone the action, but there may be a larger crime that must be investigated. The fact you knew about this ring makes me even more certain that you are guilty of something—you knew this ring was upstairs all along?~
@2783  = ~Oh, so now you've stooped to forcing your way into locked containers in people's houses, have you? Before you accuse ME of doing anything wrong, maybe you should look to YOURSELF. What are you doing breaking and entering?~
@2784  = ~~
@2785  = ~Uh... no, no, I didn't know it was locked upstairs. Look, I don't have to explain anyth—~
@2786  = ~You're right. I will take Eidan's ring to the elders of the town and let them decide how to deal with this. Perhaps they could call on Eidan's shade with the ring and speak to him about this. Justice must be served.~
@2787  = ~Look, you sniveling little dog, I'm tired of hearing your lies and your blustering—I could kill you where you stand, and claim this inn as mine and never feel a *shred* of remorse. Now tell me the truth, or I'll set you outside until you freeze, then carve you like an ice block.~
@2788  = ~Look... hold on, hold on... here's what happened. First off, I never laid a *hand* on Eidan.~
@2789  = ~So Eidan *is* dead.~
@2790  = ~Well... yeah. But it's not my fault... I come into the inn one night after barely making my way through Kuldahar Pass, see, and there he is, lying on the floor of the inn, cold as a stone. Now, I'd been through the pass before, even talked with the old fool a bit, and I knew he didn't have any family.~
@2791  = ~What did you do with the body?~
@2792  = ~There'd been rumors of people missing, so I buried the body outside of town, and then, well, I dug up some pen and ink and set up the claim. Granted, I stripped him of his belongings—and I should have thrown away that damn ring—but look, I'm not doing any harm. He didn't HAVE any family. And this town NEEDS an inn.~
@2793  = ~So why did you do it? You probably won't be able to sell this place, you know. The storm season closes off the caravan routes too often to turn any profit.~
@2794  = ~I know, it's just that... I don't know, I'm SICK of traveling, and I suddenly got the urge to settle. Blame the halfling in me, I suppose. At least I didn't try to plant myself in some glorified mole burrow and smoke a stinkweed pipe until I die of boredom.~
@2795  = ~While it's good you didn't hurt Eidan, you *shouldn't* have hid the body and falsified the claim. There were people here that probably knew him and cared for him, and they would have liked to have paid their respects. Besides, as Eidan's ring states, the inn belongs to *Kuldahar*, not you. What you did was wrong.~
