@12615 = ~Well, there's old Arundel—we've seen him talking to birds, but we figured that he was... well, a little touched in the head. Could be he knows where you'd find a druid.~
@12616 = ~Where is the house of this Arundel?~
@12617 = ~I may look for him, then. I had more questions about Kuldahar first, however.~
@12618 = ~I will seek him out, then. Farewell.~
@12619 = ~Southwest section of town, there's a two-story house embedded into the tree; looks like a big stone wall with a door. That's Arundel's house. It's just south and east of Kuldahar Run, east of the bridge.~
@12620 = ~~
@12621 = ~Well, Kuldahar's not a big place, but I can tell you a bit about it, if you want.~
@12622 = ~How long has that tree been here? It's huge.~
@12623 = ~Any place I could tip back a tankard? I've got quite a thirst.~
@12624 = ~I'm looking for a place to rest, actually.~
@12625 = ~Alyth~
@12626 = ~Avery~
@12627 = ~Any supply shops or weapon shops?~
@12628 = ~Bork~
@12629 = ~There any churches or temples nearby?~
@12630 = ~I thought I saw a... ship... lying by the great tree when I came in.~
@12631 = ~Brilla~
@12632 = ~~
@12633 = ~We saw a tower by the tree from the road. Is that your local watchtower?~
@12634 = ~~
@12635 = ~Been here as long as I can remember—a blessing as near as I can tell. The chilly weather doesn't even touch the town with the tree growing here; it radiates enough heat to keep things green, which is a sight for tired eyes here in the North. But hells, if you came through the Pass, you'll know that already.~
@12636 = ~The tree seems... weak somehow. Ill. Yet I know not why. Is there something wrong with it?~
@12637 = ~I had some more questions about the town.~
@12638 = ~I had some more questions about Kuldahar in general.~
@12639 = ~~
@12640 = ~It's more than that—it's like the great tree's influence is... shrinking somehow. We don't know why. People have had to abandon the outlying farmsteads when the temperature dropped, though. No telling what's next.~
@12641 = ~~
@12642 = ~~
@12643 = ~~
@12644 = ~Ah, you'd be looking for Whitcomb's place, the Root Cellar. You'll find that just a little southeast of the base of the great tree, in the middle of a cluster of three buildings. Keep an eye out—with the roots being as huge as they are, you can walk right over the tavern and not know it's there.~
@12645 = ~~
@12646 = ~~
@12647 = ~Well—hmmmm. There's the Evening Shade, but... well, the previous innkeeper was one of the townsfolk who's gone missing, and it's come under new ownership. Some halfling merchant from the south. Not a very friendly fellow, but I suppose the Evening Shade's all there is for travelers. You don't want to be sleeping outside with all the disappearances.~
@12648 = ~Disappearances?~
@12649 = ~~
@12650 = ~~
@12651 = ~~
@12652 = ~There's the Evening Shade—but well, I don't mean to tell tales, but from what I've heard the current owner actually found the old owner dead in the inn, and he buried the body in secret and tried to forge a claim to the inn. Very shady stuff—but he *did* come clean to the elders; a guilty conscience, I suppose. In any event, the Evening Shade's all there is for travelers. You don't want to be sleeping outside with all the disappearances.~
@12653 = ~I don't know if a guilty conscience had anything to do with it. What's this about disappearances?~
@12654 = ~~
@12655 = ~~
@12656 = ~~
@12657 = ~Aye, a lot of people have gone missing recently—one of them was Conlan's boy, Sheemish. The next morning, the whole town searched for the boy but turned up nothing. He was just gone. Vanished without a trace. Then Mother Egenia from the church, Eidan the innkeeper, Maegan Potts—and others. Not a trace of any of them. *Nothing.*~
@12658 = ~~
@12659 = ~~
@12660 = ~There's two—if weapons are what you're wanting, go see Conlan the Smith, in the northern center part of town; his forge is burning day and night, so it's hard to miss. If you're looking for general supplies, go see Gerth—his shop's near Kuldahar Run, north of the bridge. It's got a railing that runs around the edge, and juts out over the water.~
@12661 = ~~
@12662 = ~~
@12663 = ~There's a Temple to Ilmater here, in the northeast canyon, just beneath the wrecked airship. Don't know if that's your faith or not, but the Brothers and the Reverend Mother are good people.~
@12664 = ~Ilmater?~
@12665 = ~Ilmater? The Broken God, correct?~
@12666 = ~~
@12667 = ~~
@12668 = ~~
@12669 = ~~
@12670 = ~Aye, he's the god of suffering, the crying god. His priests seek to help alleviate the sufferings of others by taking on their pain. Don't know all the teachings, but that's pretty much how I understand it.~
@12671 = ~~
@12672 = ~Don't you worship him?~
@12673 = ~~
@12674 = ~~
@12675 = ~~
@12676 = ~Well, I'll tell you friend, one look at the great tree of Kuldahar, and it seems to me that nature's the only thing really deserving of worship around here. I mean—the branches nearly scrape the clouds, it seems. Beautiful sight, it is.~
@12677 = ~It gratifies me to hear of your respect for nature. I too have taken nature into my heart, and it grants me strength.~
@12678 = ~The tree is strong indeed—but it seems... weak somehow. Ill. Yet I know not why.~
@12679 = ~~
