@40405 = ~I couldn't help notice that wooden box in your pack. May I take a closer look at it?~
@40406 = ~:With the song in the air, a ghostly figure appears before you, shimmering and transparent.:~
@40407 = ~:It takes one last, sad look at the party before fading away.:~
@40408 = ~:The figure moves its mouth as if to speak, but no words come out.:~
@40409 = ~:The figure moves its mouth as if to speak, but no words come out. It gestures to the empty scabbard on its hip as it tries to speak.:~
@40410 = ~Blade... my old blade... where's my blade?~
@40411 = ~Ah, my old rousing music. It is good to see this world once again.~
@40412 = ~Only a gifted player could restore me to such clarity. For this, I must thank you, young bard.~
@40413 = ~I can teach you a few tricks with her—I think you'll find her even more useful.~
@40414 = ~Farewell, travelers.~
@40415 = ~Murdaugh, we found this old journal from a bard. Could you try playing it for us?~
@40416 = ~Let's see, let's see... this is a difficult piece, but I think I'm up to it.~
@40417 = ~Your blade? Speak plainly, spirit.~
@40418 = ~My blade... my blade...~
@40419 = ~A rousing tale to be sure, but the spirit is restless. It's looking for its old weapon.~
@40420 = ~Perhaps if you could find it, he would be at rest once again.~
@40421 = ~It is also good to see my trusty blade again, The Sword of Myrloch Vale.~
@40422 = ~You flatter me, spirit.~
@40423 = ~We have found Daen's blade, the Sword of Myrloch Vale.~
@40424 = ~Well done, travelers. Let us try the ballad once more.~
@40425 = ~Telanis, we found this ballad. Could you play it for us?~
@40426 = ~How could a bard refuse such a request? Let me see it.~
@40427 = ~You are too kind, spirit.~
@40428 = ~Accurate, yes, but much too kind.~
@40429 = ~A fellow spirit. Like many of my brethren, he seems to be out of sorts.~
@40430 = ~What is it, friend? What can we do for you?~
@40431 = ~What about it? We wish to help you.~
@40432 = ~Another poor, trapped spirit. However, it does seem like, unlike the cursed elves here, we may be able to help him.~
@40433 = ~Should you find his sword, return and we can try summoning him once more.~
@40434 = ~We think that the Sword of Myrloch Vale is the spirit's old weapon.~
@40435 = ~Indeed? Well let's try the ballad again.~
@40436 = ~What do you make of this mithral hammer?~
@40437 = ~Interesting. I believe this is the symbol of one of the local dwarven clans—the Battlehammers.~
@40438 = ~The dwarves are known for their craftmanship, and I can see it. This feels like it's magical as well.~
@40439 = ~What does it do?~
@40440 = ~Interesting. Thanks, Conlan.~
@40441 = ~Well, the dwarves are also very secretive of their methods so I can't say for sure, but it doesn't feel very... focused.~
@40442 = ~What do you mean?~
@40443 = ~It's hard to explain. Usually you can feel a... purpose to most magic. This seems... vague and fuzzy, like it wasn't enchanted with a clear goal.~
@40444 = ~If I could get a better feel for the type of magic used by these dwarves... well, just keep your eyes open for more Battlehammer items and maybe I can figure it out.~
@40445 = ~This Stoutward shield is from Clan Battlehammer.~
@40446 = ~Here, let me see that.~
@40447 = ~Yes, I can feel the similarity. Even more interesting, these seem to have an affinity for each other.~
@40448 = ~It's possible we may be able to combine them.~
@40449 = ~What would that involve?~
@40450 = ~I'd rather not risk it.~
@40451 = ~It's fairly tricky, and mithral doesn't always react well after it's been imbued.~
@40452 = ~I think I could probably add this as a standard for the shield. I'm not sure what, exactly, that would do for Stoutward's abilities.~
@40453 = ~And it's a solid day of work. But since you've rescued Sheemish, I'll waive most of the costs. How about 1,000 gold?~
@40454 = ~If you change your mind, let me know.~
@40455 = ~What else can I do for you?~
@40456 = ~Sure, that sounds like a bargain.~
@40457 = ~And it's a solid day of work. How about 4500 gold?~
@40458 = ~I don't have enough gold at the moment. Perhaps later.~
@40459 = ~When you've got the gold, I've got the time.~
@40460 = ~Come back in a day and your new shield will be ready.~
@40461 = ~What were you saying about this mithral hammer again?~
@40462 = ~Welcome back. I have successfully merged the symbol with Stoutward.~
@40463 = ~Combining them was fairly straightforward, like they were meant for each other.~
@40464 = ~Here's Stoutward back. I think you'll find it's a lot stronger now.~
@40465 = ~Can I commission armor from these white dragon scales?~
@40466 = ~Dragon! I never thought I'd see something like this.~
@40467 = ~I don't have much experience with exotic materials such as these, but I should be able to make some armor from them.~
@40468 = ~I'll take it slow—let's say three days to finish—and make sure it's right, as dragon scales don't grow on trees.~
@40469 = ~My commission is 5000 gold.~
@40470 = ~For dragon scale armor? Yes, let's do it.~
@40471 = ~Alright. Come back in three days and I should have it ready for you.~
@40472 = ~Sorry, Conlan. I'm not interested.~
@40473 = ~What was involved in making White Dragon Scale again?~
@40474 = ~Welcome back. I was just putting a last coat of polish on the white dragon armor.~
@40475 = ~Well, of course, it's your armor now.~
@40476 = ~Travel well, friend. I doubt you'll find better protection than this.~
@40477 = ~Can you help us with this Cynicism sword?~
@40478 = ~Perhaps. Weapons are not my forte, but I can certainly examine it.~
@40479 = ~Ah yes. I can see what you mean. It simply radiates cynicism and depression.~
@40480 = ~I may be able to alleviate that somewhat, but I don't have the needed spell at hand.~
@40481 = ~Do you have a scroll of Emotion, Hope? I can combine that with a permanence spell to, hopefully, relieve some of its depressing effects.~
@40482 = ~Yes, here you are.~
@40483 = ~No, but I'll return if I find one.~
@40484 = ~Good, good. Excuse me for a moment, I don't want to do magic in front of my customers.~
@40485 = ~How else may I be of service?~
@40486 = ~There we are. I couldn't quite cheer it up entirely but it's much improved.~
@40487 = ~I've brought some Emotion, Hope scrolls for you.~
@40488 = ~Yeti Hide Armor +1~
@40489 = ~Here you go.~
@40490 = ~Why do you want to see it?~
@40491 = ~It appears to be a collection of gnomish tools. There may be something there I could use to repair my airship.~
@40492 = ~Oh yes, look at this! Where did you find this?~
@40493 = ~It was in a yeti cave.~
@40494 = ~That's none of your business.~
@40495 = ~Does it really matter?~
@40496 = ~I guess it doesn't really matter. I was merely curious.~
@40497 = ~Yes, I think this could be very useful to me. And, I suspect, probably just deadweight for adventurers.~
@40498 = ~For the toolbox, I'm willing to part with some of my best potions. I think those may be more useful in your travels than some musty old toolbox.~
@40499 = ~Sorry, Oswald, but I'd really rather have some gold.~
@40500 = ~I'm interested... but what kind of potions?~
@40501 = ~That sounds fair. You've got yourself a deal, Oswald.~
@40502 = ~Ha! Think a bit of coin might be more useful! Fair enough, but I don't think I have as much coin to offer as potions. How does 150 gold sound?~
@40503 = ~What potions, then, could you offer?~
@40504 = ~Sorry Oswald, I'm not interested.~
@40505 = ~Agreed.~
@40506 = ~How about two potions of healing, a potion of invisibility, and a potion of heroism?~
@40507 = ~Excellent, excellent. Now is there anything else I can help you with? Something from my stock, perhaps?~
@40508 = ~I don't think you'll get a better offer. Ask around, and if you change your mind, come back and see me.~
@40509 = ~Is there anything else I can help you with? Something from my stock, perhaps?~
@40510 = ~Are you still interested in these tools?~
@40511 = ~Yes I am. My offer remains two potions of healing, a potion of invisibility, and a potion of heroism.~
@40512 = ~On second thought, I'm still not ready to sell these.~
@40513 = ~Welcome back. I heard from Orrick that you bought the Girdle of Gond from him. I had my eye on that Girdle for some time but didn't act fast enough.~
@40514 = ~I have a proposal that may be beneficial to both of us, if you'll hear me out.~
@40515 = ~I wanted to examine the Girdle to see how it works—what enchantments have been used, how it's assembled—in the hopes that I may be able to make one myself.~
@40516 = ~If you would be willing to part with it for a day... let's call it a loan... I would be most grateful.~
@40517 = ~Sure Oswald, if it'll help your studies.~
@40518 = ~I know too many gnomes. You're not going to take it apart, are you?~
@40519 = ~I'll need some collateral.~
@40520 = ~Sorry Oswald, I need this for my travels.~
@40521 = ~Oh, err, no, of course not.~
@40522 = ~Well, then go ahead.~
@40523 = ~I'm afraid I don't have much I can spare at the moment. Would you take 50 gold?~
@40524 = ~If that's all you have, just take the belt. I don't need the gold.~
@40525 = ~Yeah, 50 gold is fine.~
@40526 = ~Thank you! A day should be enough to sort out your little secrets...~
@40527 = ~Did you still want to borrow the Girdle of Gond?~
@40528 = ~Thank you for loaning me your Girdle of Gond. I've learned a great deal more than I had thought I would.~
@40529 = ~So much, in fact, that I think I can make it work even better.~
@40530 = ~With a few more enchantments, I think I can incorporate some of the tools from that dusty old toolbox you sold to me.~
@40531 = ~The spell components are pretty costly, though. I'd need at least 1200 gold to get it done.~
@40532 = ~The spell components are pretty costly, though. I'd need at least 1600 gold to get it done.~
@40533 = ~That sounds great. Let's do it.~
@40534 = ~That sounds interesting, but you'll have to give me some time to raise that much gold.~
@40535 = ~No, I just want my Girdle back.~
@40536 = ~Well, then here's your Girdle back. If you change your mind, I'd love to do some tinkering.~
@40537 = ~I'll begin immediately. Come back in a day or so and I'll have it ready.~
@40538 = ~Hello again friends. I'm pleased to have your completed belt.~
@40539 = ~I've added more pouches and added some tools. You should be able to tackle better locks and traps now.~
@40540 = ~You can still upgrade the Girdle of Gond, right?~
@40541 = ~Can you tell me more about Bren Muller?~
@40542 = ~Ah. You ask not for Bren Muller, but for his crossbow, yes?~
@40543 = ~Bren Muller was more than a scholar, but a mage of some repute.~
@40544 = ~Unusually for a mage, he relied on a crossbow. Even more unusual was his incredible accuracy.~
@40545 = ~It is believed that he took great pains to build and enchant his crossbow to maximize his accuracy.~
@40546 = ~Not only is it unusually accurate, but it can be boosted even further for a short period of time.~
@40547 = ~As a necromancer, can you decipher this text on the Mystery of the Dead?~
@40548 = ~Let me see... I can decipher some of it, yes. It's a very ancient dialect of, I believe, eastern necromancers.~
@40549 = ~It appears to be spell incantations. I think this shield may be able to cast spells, if we can decrypt this text.~
@40550 = ~I'd be willing to do so, for a price. As I mentioned before, I'm interested in buying armor to barter with the spirits of the island.~
@40551 = ~They seem to prefer old, rusted shells of armor. Bring me three of them and I'll translate your text.~
@40552 = ~Here you are.~
@40553 = ~I'll be back with some armor.~
@40554 = ~Perfect, just what I'm looking for. The translation shouldn't take more than a few hours to complete.~
@40555 = ~Is there anything else you need?~
@40556 = ~We have brought three suits of armor. Can you translate the text on Mystery of the Dead now?~
@40557 = ~I have translated as much text as possible. Some of it is simply beyond me, but I have deciphered two incantations.~
@40558 = ~One is for repelling undead, and the other appears to be a healing spell.~
@40559 = ~Do you know anything about the Young Rage axe?~
@40560 = ~Can't say I've heard o' it, laddie. Let me hold it for a moment.~
@40561 = ~Aye, I can feel the rage of my kin again't the one who forced them to make it.~
@40562 = ~'Tis a terrible thing, but ye need more 'en me. Ye need the help of a necromancer.~
@40563 = ~Edion, over on the barbarians' burial isle, is a necromancer.~
@40564 = ~We have a necromancer in our party.~
@40565 = ~If I meet one, I'll come back.~
@40566 = ~Anything else ye be wantin'?~
@40567 = ~Do ye now? Well, I can do my part. Once we're done here, take the axe to 'im.~
@40568 = ~He'll need to put their spirits to rest.~
@40569 = ~Lend me your necromancer and let's get started.~
@40570 = ~There we go. I've done me part, now ye need to take this to Edion.~
@40571 = ~This scroll explains what he has to do.~
@40572 = ~What were you saying about the Young Rage axe again?~
@40573 = ~What do I need to do with Young Rage again?~
@40574 = ~Take that note to your necromancer friend over on the Burial Isle so he can put the spirits in the axe to rest.~
@40575 = ~I need you to banish the spirits of Young Rage.~
@40576 = ~You need me to—what?~
@40577 = ~A blind dwarven smith said we can banish the spirits plaguing this axe with the aid of a necromancer. He sent instructions.~
@40578 = ~Let me see that.~
@40579 = ~Yes, this seems straightforward enough. I'll need 300 gold for my services.~
@40580 = ~Perhaps we'll do this later.~
@40581 = ~It's a simple exorcism, for a cost of 300 gold.~
@40582 = ~What's needed for the Young Rage axe again?~
@40583 = ~Aye, thanks for yer help with the spirits. The rage trapped in the axe has been put to rest.~
@40584 = ~Welcome back. I have your cloak ready, though I had forgotten how much I hate working with fur. I hope you enjoy it, for I will not be making another.~
@40585 = ~From the reek, you can probably tell your yeti hide armor is ready. It will take many months for the smell to leave, and I will not be working with any more yeti pelts.~
@40586 = ~Orrick may be able to make something out of those pelts, too.~
@40587 = ~Mirek mentioned you may be able to do something with these winter wolf pelts.~
@40588 = ~Mirek mentioned you may be able to do something with these yeti pelts.~
@40589 = ~How about winter wolf pelts?~
@40590 = ~What about yeti pelts?~
@40591 = ~The pelts can be sewn together into a cloak. With a few cantrips, we can preserve some of the winter wolf's natural protections in the cloak.~
@40592 = ~But it takes a lot of raw material and work. I'd need at least five pelts and 3500 gold.~
@40593 = ~That sounds great. Let's do it.~
@40594 = ~No, I don't think I'm interested.~
@40595 = ~Yeti pelts are not the best of materials to work with, but Conlan and myself may be able to make some hide armor out of them.~
@40596 = ~It's a bit tougher and stiffer than leather. I'll be able to lay some enchantments into the materials as they cure.~
@40597 = ~It'll take a lot of material, though, and some pricey spell components. We'll probably need 10 pelts and, oh, 2500 gold.~
@40598 = ~Excellent. I shall send these to the seamstress straightaway. Come back in a day or so and I'll have your cloak ready.~
@40599 = ~Very well. I'll go and talk with Conlan about making some armor and enchanting it. Return in three days or so.~
@40600 = ~Can I help you with anything else?~
@40601 = ~Can you do anything with these remorhaz shells?~
@40602 = ~Sure. I know some craftsmen who can make helmets out of them. It'll cost 8000 gold.~
@40603 = ~I need some time to gather that much gold.~
@40604 = ~Thanks for the information.~
@40605 = ~Come back in three days and I'll have your helmet ready.~
@40606 = ~Anything else I can do for you?~
@40607 = ~Is my helmet ready yet, Dirty Llew?~
@40608 = ~Here you are.~
@40609 = ~Sure. I know some craftsmen who can make helmets out of them. It'll cost 7000 gold.~
@40610 = ~For you, my lovely, I know some craftsmen who can make helmets out of them. It'll cost 5000 gold.~
@40611 = ~Gond, god of invention and artifice, is a deity rarely worshipped by traditional adventurers. Some thieves, however, revere Gond for his role in the development of locks, traps, and other complex machines. One such thief was the burglar Jurmar the Calm, who began his career as a locksmith. Known for his cool demeanor and steady hand, Jurmar paid priests of Gond to fashion this tool belt for him. Whenever Jurmar was stuck in a situation where he didn't have the right tool for a job, one of the small pouches on the belt would supply him with what he needed.

Oswald has managed to add even more tools for the belt, further enhancing its usefulness.

STATISTICS:

Equipped abilities:
– Open Locks: +15%
– Find Traps: +10%

Weight: 2~
@40612 = ~Hide armor is made from the thick hide of a very large animal (yeti, in this case) or from many layers of normal leather from common animals, like cows. Hide armor is far too bulky, inflexible and heavy to be used much in advanced human cultures. However, among the barbaric humanoid masses throughout the dark forests and misty jungles of the world, hide armor is common. Even though it does offer more protection than leather armor, one must get by the offensive odor and shoddy appearance in order to wear it effectively. Even though Thieves can wear this armor, it has a negative effect on their abilities.

This particular set of armor was cured by Conlan and enchanted by Orrick. Orrick was not able to quite get rid of its inherited weakness against fire, though it offers some natural protection against cold.

